<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-484-556  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 484 556.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  August 1 1989 v3 n28 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lawsuit buys time for System 7. (Apple Macintosh operating systemversion 7.0) (editorial)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>Lawsuit buys time for System 7andM;After so much legal posturing, the Apple-Microsoft interface suit is finallygetting to the heart of the issue.andM;By excluding 178 of the 189 visual displays in Windows 2.03 from theinfringement suit, Judge William Schwarzer has narrowed the focus of the caseto the matter of overlapping windows and the use of a few specific icons.andM;Despite statements from Apple's lawyers that they expected and welcome thisdecision, it has nevertheless been widely interpreted as a victory forMicrosoft, which will now be able to focus its arguments on the question ofwhether Apple's own use of overlapping windows was derived from the XeroxStar interface.andM;There may be merit to the argument that the total experience embodied in theMac interface amounts to more than the sum of its individual elements.andP;  Ifso, that line of reasoning apparently is no longer available to Apple.andM;Microsoft is so sure of its position that it will now petition for a summaryjudgment.andP;  But it seems likely that the court will let the limited case go totrial.andP;  If so, the matter will continue unresolved for many more months,which may be all the victory that Apple needs.andM;MacWEEK has argued all along that Apple is engaged in a tactical battle formarket advantage rather than a strategic confrontation over fundamental legalissues.andP;  By using the copyright issue to cast a cloud over the market forMicrosoft's Windows and Presentation Manager, Apple has bought time toimprove its own system software.andM;Apple needs just four to six months more to get System 7 into the hands ofdevelopers and users.andP;  Even if it ends up losing the case, Apple will be awinner if it makes use of the time gained in the courtroom to gain back itsedge in technology.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>